SIMPLE: pity
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pity
<hw>Pit"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Pities</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE. <ets>pite</ets>, OF.
<ets>pit⟦eacute⟧</ets>, <ets>piti⟦eacute⟧</ets>, F.
<ets>piti⟦eacute⟧</ets>, L. <ets>pietas</ets> piety, kindness, pity. See
<er>Pious</er>, and cf. <er>Piety</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Piety.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Wyclif.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A feeling for the sufferings or distresses of
another or others; sympathy with the grief or misery of another;
compassion; fellow-feeling; commiseration.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He that hath <qex>pity</qex> upon the poor lendeth unto the
Lord.</q> <rj><qau>Prov. xix. 17.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He . . . has no more <qex>pity</qex> in him than a dog.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A reason or cause of pity, grief, or regret; a thing
to be regretted.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The more the <xex>pity</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What <qex>pity</qex> is it⟦br⟧
That we can die but once to serve our country!</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In this sense, sometimes used in the plural, especially
in the colloquialism: ⟦ldquo⟧It is a thousand
<xex>pities</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Compassion; mercy; commiseration; condolence;
sympathy, fellow-suffering; fellow-feeling. -- <er>Pity</er>,
<er>Sympathy</er>, <er>Compassion</er>. <xex>Sympathy</xex> is literally
<xex>fellow-feeling</xex>, and therefore requiers a certain degree of
equality in situation, circumstances, etc., to its fullest exercise.
<xex>Compassion</xex> is deep tenderness for another under severe or
inevitable misfortune. <xex>Pity</xex> regards its object not only as
suffering, but <xex>weak</xex>, and hence as inferior.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pity</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Pity
<hw>Pit"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Pitied</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Pitying</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To feel pity or
compassion for; to have sympathy with; to compassionate; to commiserate;
to have tender feelings toward (any one), awakened by a knowledge of
suffering.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Like as a father <qex>pitieth</qex> his children, so the Lord
<qex>pitieth</qex> them that fear him.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. ciii.
13.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To move to pity; -- used impersonally.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It <qex>pitieth</qex> them to see her in the dust.</q>
<rj><qau>Bk. of Com. Prayer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pity</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Pity
<hw>Pit"y</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To be compassionate; to show
pity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will not <qex>pity</qex>, nor spare, nor have mercy.</q>
<rj><qau>Jer. xiii. 14.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pitying</ent>⟦br⟧
